abstract: The Carter Handicap at Aqueduct and the Excelsior Handicap at Jamaica have each been increased to $10,000 guaranteed money. abstract: WASHINGTON, Feb. 17. -- A special statistical report of the Inter-State Commerce Commission just made shows that railway capitalization has very rapidly increased during the last few years. The total capitalization for the year ended June 30, 1893, was $9,894,625,239, or $59,729 per mile. Three years later it increased to $10,566,863,771, or $59,610 per mile, while in 1904 it had grown to $13,213,124,679, or $64,265 per mile.

abstract: Men and women at work in the wholesale houses near Houston and Greene Streets yesterday morning, about 11 o'clock, heard a crash. The article which it heads describes how the striking printers in Chicago, being at odds with the "non-union" firm which prints the City Directory, have undertaken to compel every labor union man in Chicago to give his name to the canvassers for the Directory as John Smith, the object, of course, being to render the work issued by the hated firm worthless.

abstract: New charges of graft in the Department of Street Cleaning will be raised in the Board of Aldermen to-day when Alderman Grifenhagen and the other members of the Committee on Street Cleaning press their investigation. abstract: ALBANY, Feb. 27. -- Voting machines for New York City must be purchased by the Board of Estimate and Apportionment if the Stanley Voting Machine bill, unanimously reported out of the Assembly Cities Committee to-night, becomes a law.
